# Temperature and Reaction Rate Investigation

## Context

In this experiment, I investigated how temperature affects the rate of reaction between calcium carbonate and hydrochloric acid. We measured the volume of carbon dioxide produced over time at 24°C, 30°C, and 40°C using a gas syringe.

## What I Learned

The results showed that higher temperatures increased the rate of reaction. The 40°C experiment produced carbon dioxide faster than the 30°C and 24°C experiments. This happened because particles at higher temperatures have more kinetic energy, move faster, and collide more frequently.

I also learned that reaction rate is explained by collision theory. At the beginning of the reaction, there are many reactant particles available, so successful collisions happen frequently and gas is produced quickly. As the reaction continues, reactants are used up, resulting in fewer successful collisions and a slower reaction rate. Eventually, the reaction stops when one of the reactants is exhausted.

## Experimental Reflection

Our group's data was not perfect, and we used some data from other groups because our experiment encountered errors. This helped me realize the importance of accurate data collection and experimental design.

Some possible improvements include:

* Using multiple trials and calculating averages.
* Improving coordination when recording time and volume measurements.
* Reducing gas loss at the start of the experiment.
* Using more consistent measurement procedures.

## Key Scientific Idea

A higher temperature increases the frequency and energy of particle collisions, leading to a faster reaction rate. This experiment provided real evidence supporting collision theory.

## Question That Stayed With Me

How can scientists reduce experimental errors while still collecting data quickly during fast chemical reactions?
